üíîrp @dxepriya when i reached inside of this baby calf's hutch, what i saw broke me. she was covered in diarrhea, which for calves can be extremely deadly. her filthy hutch had no bedding, no water, and no food. the only thing she could call her own is the ear-tag that was forcibly pierced into her ear when she was just a few days old. but the most haunting part of this experience was how lonely she was.
her loneliness is a routine practice in the dairy industry which depends on separating mothers from their babies. when julianne, alicia and i found angel at raymar ranch, she too was separated from her mom. but not only that, angel was thrown away like trash in a graveyard, waiting to die.

when i tried to help angel, she was ripped away from my arms. why is it that the industry sees us helping animals, their response is to punish us? it's because the truth is so scary that they feel it's criminal to publicize it.

if animal rights activists are considered criminals for trying to save baby cows from a life of misery and loneliness, we need more, not less of us. #dairyfree #dairy #govegan #crueltyfree #meat #hamburger #burger #pizzahut #pizzapizza #ilovepizza #cheesecake #cheesecakefactory #cheesey #cheeseboard #creamy #cream #creamcheese #dairyisscary #stopseparatingfamilies #burgerking #tacobell #burrito #quesadilla #vegano #metoo #seperation #donttakeourplanetforgranted (via #easyrepost @appkottage)

text:
üîÆüíÄü¶¥ it was difficult to put down tomi adeyemi‚Äôs children of blood and bone. although it started off a bit slow, it grew in epic proportions, ‚Äúknocking me off my feet‚Äù time and time again. one word: women. all powerful women. strong women. women not to be messed with. independent women. women who grow from adversity. women who grow from trauma. men played the sidekicks in the first of adeyemi‚Äôs trilogy. in the day and age of the #metoo movement, having men take a backseat role was refreshing. adeyemi notes that cobab is about the oppression and persecution faced by people of color in this country. she says, ‚Äúi told myself that if just one person could read [the book] and have their heads or minds changed, then i would‚Äôve done something meaningful against a problem that often feels so much bigger than myself.‚Äù taking these two real world issues, and weaving them into a fantastical world is what makes adeyemi‚Äôs book so dang powerful. ‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
the two main characters, z√©lie and amari, are complex. one is a fighter, gifted with magic over the living and the dead. the other is a princess, struggling against the expectations set upon her, finally seeing the blood the monarchy was built upon. they, along with z√©lie‚Äôs brother, and a lionaire (a magical creature), are traveling to bring magic back to a world that has long been without it. ‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
adeyemi, a nigerian-american author, incorporates west african folklore, language, landscapes, and ideas. at times, i was a bit lost, and wished for a glossary in the back of the book. however, i was a guest in the presence of a storyteller. this was adeyemi‚Äôs story to tell, and my job, as the reader, was not only to enjoy, but to learn. i acclimated, as minorities in this country are ‚Äúexpected‚Äù to do. after i did, i was more in awe than before. ‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
i picked this book up at a time when i needed an escape, and welcomed the chance to dig into a new adventure. ‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£

text:
most days it's me vs me. ... these last few it's been me vs this guy... who represents "the reoccurring bully" that i've never stood up to since i was 9 years old. ... until last week. üåü
last week i spoke up.. and after facing something that i've been carrying around with me for literally 22 years .. so much is happening. the strangest and most fascinating to me is that i immediately lost 4 lbs. <---which has me wondering<--- is the stuff we are carrying around literally weighing us down? ü§î üåü 
this week during my workouts so much is purging and coming to the surface.. so much i didn't even know was there lingering and probably affecting my quality of life..it bubbles up and oozes out of my pores and my heart. i get angry. i cry. i focus. i allow this process.  to accept. to learn. to grow and to fuel me. and also ...gulp. to forgive. because forgiveness, my friends... doesn't take the other person off the hook. but it takes the hook out of you. üåü
i am not my past. i am not those men. i am not victim minded.  i am a champion. i am an overcomer. i am victorious. i am a daughter of the king. and i. will. not. quit. <---this war isn't over; so much is surfacing and new experiences resulting, like anxiety, etc but using the tools i have in my mindset toolbox i know for sure that i get to champion through this and not fall victim. and you can do the same üåü friends, if you are facing something challenging right now, i believe in you!  if you feel so inclined, drop it in comments belowüëá we got this üí™
.
.
#victory #metoo #wegotthis #sweatforsuccess  #mindset #success #motivation #why #abusesurvivor #survivor #mothersofdaughters #imnottakingit #champion #humility #community #spousalrape #control #freedom #manipulation #personalpower

domestic abuse is domestic abuse no matter who it comes from. it doesn't matter if it leave a mark. it doesn't matter if you say something or not, it will be domestic abuse, and if you don't stand up, someone else will for you. and you cannot resent them for breaking up your family/relationship. they saved you. you should be thankful youre not with them anymore. you were with them for their looks, that's why you stayed. that isn't love. abuse isn't love. it never will be.

text:
my dear friend @fiiiyoniii created this amazing list of questions that are helpful to ask you current or potential sexual partners. i separated them into 4 categories to make it easier to digest and choose which things feel most important to you at the time.
.
can you imagine if this was taught as sex ed in our high schools or college? how would our sexual interactions be different if we took the time to discuss boundaries, expectations, our history, and emotions with partners? there are so many beautiful conversations to be had between two people based on this list but also just to become aware of your own truth by thinking about how you would answer each of these questions.
.
in a post #metoo world, these kinds of communication tools are so useful to start to build new ways of relating and creating containers for open and honest communication. it‚Äôs probably too much to ask them all in one session, but even starting with the questions in the ‚Äúsafety‚Äù category before engaging with a new person would change the whole interaction and help both people feel comfortable and confident going into a sexy situation. or maybe you ask the questions and decide it‚Äôs not a good match and save you both a lot of drama and heartbreak...
.
comment with other questions that you feel like could be added to this list and please share with your friends! i have printed copies here in new orleans i‚Äôd be happy to give people and i can send the file if anyone wants to print out copies and distribute them to their friends + community :)
.
#safesex #consent #sexquestions #sextalk #communication #boundaries #sex #sexed #sexytime #nomeansno #yesmeansyes #ecstaticconsent

text:
y‚Äôall wanna know something crazy? ‚Å£
‚Å£
there‚Äôs two viral videos you may have seen that you didn‚Äôt realize were connected in any way. but they‚Äôre intrinsically, almost ironically, miraculously so. ‚Å£
‚Å£
one that was essentially my late husband talking to our daughter, who was then 7 months old on a brown couch. he was 27. he had cancer. he was dying. and, he was telling her how big god‚Äôs plan for her life was, that he regretted he wouldn‚Äôt be here to watch it unfold, but that he trusted she would be well taken care of. that video has now been viewed over 94 million times, world wide, & has been translated into multiple languages. i prayed so hard he would be healed y‚Äôall. i would have traded my life. we did everything we could. but, he passed away two months later. ‚Å£
‚Å£
the second video was me talking to our daughter, now five years old, adopted by my second husband. i was telling her that a little baby was growing in my tummy. she had big faith that god would pull through with a sister for her. and, she told us that day that she‚Äôd been praying for one. she didn‚Äôt know i‚Äôd already experienced two miscarriages. this is a story of answered prayers... it‚Äôs gone viral in its own right, at 3.9 million views last i saw. ‚Å£
‚Å£
two videos. two stories. same little girl. the end of one life. the beginning of another... prayers that seemed to go unanswered & another set that came fully true. ‚Å£
‚Å£
i don‚Äôt think many people realize that the small bald baby in the first video that lost her daddy is the same girl now blonde & grown & believing in a god who is bigger than life .... & bigger than death. ‚Å£
‚Å£
many people saw the first video & questioned my husband‚Äôs sanity. ‚Äúhow could you believe in a god that loves you when he‚Äôs doing this to you??‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
y‚Äôall, i had the same question then. and, it only got worse after he died. it was only once i let go of who i thought god *should* be, that i opened myself up to truth & to miracles & to seeing past what this world has to offer... that i figured out who our creator really is. ‚Å£
‚Å£
he is love. his ways are crazy mysterious & confusing as heck sometimes. but, in the end, he is working all things... the good and even the bad things...

text:
i was on call with a client this week and we were talking about what she called, ‚Äúdance anxiety‚Äù. she used to be the wallflower at parties, never went to see live music and if she did just chair danced. (mind you, she and i did not start working together over dancing)

so she‚Äôs describing how separate she felt.  so self conscious and so frustrated with herself. 
a few months ago she started a new practice- morning dance parties with the kids in the kitchen.  the kids were happier and easier to handle in the morning and her mood improved.  a lot. 
then she started walking more.  then she lost 15 lbs.  then she searched out dance classes and is just one thing, completely indulgent that she does for herself once a week- pole dancing with other women. 
her relationship started to improve.  they started talking more.  what seemed impossible had hope. 
and it all started with dancing in the kitchen.

i have a morning wobble party with the dogs every morning.  i dance on hikes, i see as much live music as i can and it wasn‚Äôt that long ago, i was also looking wantonly at the women dancing wishing i could play too

what sounds like a silly thing you don‚Äôt have time for could make ripples out into every area of your life. 
why?  we get into our body and out of our head.  we breathe.  we release the cuddle hormone, oxytocin which has us feel safe and learn faster.  and it‚Äôs fun üòä

what‚Äôs your jam?

translation: it's said that those people who don't have anyone, god is there for them. but if we only live expecting that god will come and help us, then that's not going to happen. this is why we are told in our ancient texts that we have to work in order to achieve our goals.

but still, there are some other people who also work hard,but they're not fortunate enough to get basic amenities, to fulfill their basic needs. there are some people who are only dependent on their day and night bread and butter, but sometimes, they have to sacrifice with only one time meal. we find utmost happiness in serving these people.

recently, in a camp organized by ngo, we found that those women who belonged to below poverty line (bpl) were having severe health issues.
we people come in this world, earn money and wish to live a luxurious and an opulent lifestyle. but in this race of living a lifestyle like that, we tend to forget our own people. those people who expect us to support them.
in order to spread this word, ngo has time and again tried to reach out to as many people as possible and asked them to help anyone who needs it.
name: Jeevan Arth Foundation (NGO)

translation: it is said that those people who do not have anyone, god is there for them. but if we only live expecting that god will come and help us, then that's not going to happen. this is why we are told in our ancient texts that we have to work in order to achieve our goals.

but still, there are some other people who also work hard,but they're not fortunate enough to get basic amenities, to fulfill their basic needs. there are some people who are only dependent on their day and night bread and butter, but sometimes, they have to sacrifice with only one time meal. we find utmost happiness in serving these people.

recently, in a camp organized by ngo, we found that those women who belonged to below poverty line (bpl) were having severe health issues.
we people come in this world, earn money and wish to live a luxurious and an opulent lifestyle. but in this race of living a lifestyle like that, we tend to forget our own people. those people who expect us to support them.
in order to spread this word, ngo has time and again tried to reach out to as many people as possible and asked them to help anyone who needs it.

text:
"unbreakable"
do me a favor sit down & take look back over your life. think about all the things, people, circumstances & challenges that was designed to break you...but yet you still here & you still standing! my point stop focusing on what could have or almost destroyed you but be thankful that god has sustained you, is still blessing you & given you strength you had no idea you possessed. when i look back i see that i was still able to smile in the midst of my banged up moments in life & that smile was evidence that there was hope for my future & that i am a living testimony so start letting the #survivor in you come forth in full life as you realize you were only "damaged" because god's children are " unbreakable" üôåüôåüôå #metoo. #mentalhealth #jesusdesirestosaveyou #lifecoach #livelaughlove #rape #rapesurvivor #rapevictim #blacklove #blackpanther #nomore #unbreakable #beencouraged #treysongz #tiffanyhaddish #obedienceisbetterthansacrifice #beyonce #ladygaga #speakupspeakout #speaklife #willsmith #reginaking #angelabassett #michelleobama #laviniasmiles #laviniaspeaks

text:
i admire them because these girls/women give us a reason to improve and make ourselves better.

yes, we men too. 
since centuries, we have believed  that women are delicate. no matter how much they try, they can't be equal to men.

this had put us on pedestal. this had made us think that we're superior.

perhaps, that's the reason we don't even think once before trolling or moral lecturing them.

recently one of the girls i follow on instagram @sakshiguptayoga
had put a post in which her armpit hairs were visible. 
that's completely her choice and people should've respected that.

yet she was trolled badly. just because they felt what she did was against the culture. 
but she is a strong woman who stood true to her belief.

when we see these strong women challenging stereotypes, standing against injustice, and making themselves stronger than us - we are inspired to improve.

we are motivated to change ourselves. we are motivated to make ourselves better.

and that's a good thing. we need more women like her. 
and as men, we have to start respecting women.

you don't necessarily need to put them on a pedestal by respecting them as a devi. 
just begin respecting them as humans. 
thank you 
#women #strongwomen #respect #humanism #humanist
#society #writersofinstagram #poetsofinstagram #awareness #metoo 
@women.slogans @womenpioneer @aahoo__ @themeltingwords @sakshiguptayoga 
@redheadwayfarer

text: hi, i‚Äôm regan. (almost) dr. g‚Äôs sidekick and daughter. at moments of being plagued with chronic health issues and ptsd. my mom made a desperate attempt to help me by guiding me through processes she had used and developed to help herself through her own traumas. thankfully they worked and this got us started on the path to finding the osage institute. since then, i‚Äôve helped develop and test every process. i‚Äôve gone from bedridden, traumatized and feeling trapped in a life i never intended to live, to a life that has turned out better than i could‚Äôve hoped for. i‚Äôm married to my wonderful husbie and best friend. i‚Äôm also the mother to a sweet exuberant toddler. g and i are still finding new ways to transform our trauma and gain more vitality. we‚Äôre excited to share our lives and techniques with you. in our circle suffering is optional, and we‚Äôd like to extend that option to you.

#repost @syaiesh
„Éª„Éª„Éª
i came across this post a few days ago and it immediately struck a cord. we suffer as young doctors, not because of increased demands of our jobs and training, but also at the hand of higher professionals that lack the basics of teaching and nourishing the future generations in medical practice. i have personally suffered at the hands of trainers who projected their own insecurities and lack of professionalism and perhaps prior unfortunate pain inflicted by their own trainers with some embarking on personal vendettas. 
there has to be a means to assess trainers based on their competency of how they teach and deliver knowledge with respect and dignity and not what they teach. trainers have to be able to separate their lives and prior psychological experiences from their teaching rather than contributing to a sad trajectory, or simply they should not be allowed to teach irrespective of the value of their knowledge or medical experience. 
hang in there everyone. not because it will get better, but because we will rise up in a movement! #metoo

text:
*trigger warning for assualt/rape*

sometimes you can feel that all this stuff about birth rights, about women having say over their body, is a lot of fuss, when everybody is working towards the same outcome. but let me tell you, body autonomy is so serious that if you don't give consent then any doctor or midwife who does something to your body is committing assault. 
today is my daughter's 23rd birthday. it was a straightforward birth but i was given a sweep against my wishes, was put on a monitor for no reason when i had asked not to be, a midwife put her hand on my tummy without asking, which made my contraction disappear instantly, and i was physically pushed down from kneeling upright, which also took away my contractions. all these things were done by well-meaning staff trying to be helpful but they invaded my body, disturbed my birth, and took away my power. 
my story is a mild one. any treatment, observation, or intervention with without your consent is assault. any hand or instrument in your vagina without your consent is rape. 
birth rape is real. it happens. imagine being naked, strapped to a bed, with your legs held up and open. people are talking about you, but you can't hear what is being said. you might ask what is going on, but no one responds. you are frighten your baby's life, or your life, might be in danger. someone you don't know, who might not even have spoken to you, goes up to your bottom and puts their hand in your vagina. maybe several people. someone cuts your genitals. they insert something, or several things, into your vagina. sounds like rape to me. feels like rape to the women who told me stories like this one. 
when women feel supported and listened to, where they are treated respectfully, and involved in every decision, they experience the birth as positive, even if they receive every intervention under the sun. but when  woman are ignored, demeaned, denied, shouted out, and/or physically assaulted they are damaged by a traumatic life experience and are likely to suffer post traumatic stress disorder. 
we are seeing a rise in ptsd in women, and their birth partners, following birth. this is not necessary. it needs to stop.

text:
wondering wednesday.
i just read an article on an interview with idris elba. he was asked whether it is harder to be a man in hollywood with the #metoo movement going strong. his response was golden "it's only hard when you're a man with something to hide." brilliant. 
but it also made me think:

what nobody seems to ever talk about really (at least not as prolonged and in detail or with as much attention or representation in the media) is the fact that men also experience harassment, sexual harassment, abuse and violence on a shockingly high level. and not necessarily from other men... and that when ever they do come out and say they are being sexually abused/harassed by their (female) partner they basically get either laughed out of town, accused of lying, told to man up and not be a wussbag or all of the above. 
it's sad really, since equality (at least in my head) means equal rights, equal treatment and equal responsibility for all... yes, women get abused and harassed and shouldn't have to put up with it on any level - but neither should men.
if we want to have a healthy society we need to acknowledge that anything can happen to anyone regardless of gender, religion, skin color or nationality and that if we want to have the equality we seem to crave we need to actually treat people equally.

#thoughtful #equality #mentoo #womentoo #wetoo #nodifferent #listen #notfunny #worthy #dontdiscriminate #showkindness #inittogether #bekind #allofus #christian #muslim #jewish #hindu #religion #gay #streight #girl #boy #gender #lgbt #humanity

text: ‚Äúself-imposed pillory‚Äù/ self-deprecating humor bc humiliation draws a crowd but abandonment is emptiness... anyone who really knows me knows no one can roast myself like i can. it‚Äôs so much easier when they are laughing with you than at you. ‚Äî‚Äîbut she didn‚Äôt laugh when i told my jokes. at first it hurt me... her awkward silences at my cutting wit... it usually broke down even the most unwilling .... then she said ‚Äúalthough you are funny, you say so many demeaning things about yourself in such a way i am not convinced you don‚Äôt actually believe them.‚Äù i wanted to laugh like it was absurd, but then i remembered all those ‚Äúfriends‚Äù who laughed ‚Äúwith‚Äù me ... then grew to disrespect me because well...i taught them to... hadn‚Äôt i? because inadvertently i had taught everyone who loved me that to do so they had to laugh at me. that‚Äôs what i rewarded. i created the disrespect i found myself surrounded by. i felt ‚Äúsafe‚Äù because they expected from me nothing more than a joke and then for sure they‚Äôd never leave me....because at the very very least i knew i was never as low as the jokes i told about myself . so here‚Äôs the thing... i don‚Äôt want to be a joke, however witty it is. i have worked too hard and have overcome too much to just be a joke. i no longer care if someone laughs at me or leaves me, i‚Äôm gonna stop making a joke of myself. ‚Äî-and to you... thank you so so much for not laughing when i was so easily laughing at myself. ty for reminding me i am not a joke. you taught me the best reason to not laugh ever.  wip #womeninart #contemporaryart #artoftheday #artofvisuals #artofinstagram #painting #sorrynotsorry #confessions #writersofinstagram #joke #colourpop #artsy #art #artist #laart #metoo #figurative #queerart #lesbianart #selfdeprecation #sketch #artjournal #loveyourself #artinla #emergingart #mixedmedia #newmedia

text:
*trigger warning for assualt/rape*

sometimes you can feel that all this stuff about birth rights, about women having say over their body, is a lot of fuss, when everybody is working towards the same outcome. but let me tell you, body autonomy is so serious that if you don't give consent then any doctor or midwife who does something to your body is committing assault. 
today is my daughter's 23rd birthday. it was a straightforward birth but i was given a sweep against my wishes, was put on a monitor for no reason when i had asked not to be, a midwife put her hand on my tummy without asking, which made my contraction disappear instantly, and i was physically pushed down from kneeling upright, which also took away my contractions. all these things were done by well-meaning staff trying to be helpful but they invaded my body, disturbed my birth, and took away my power. 
my story is a mild one. any treatment, observation, or intervention with without your consent is assault. any hand or instrument in your vagina without your consent is rape. 
birth rape is real. it happens. imagine being naked, strapped to a bed, with your legs held up and open. people are talking about you, but you can't hear what is being said. you might ask what is going on, but no one responds. you are frighten your baby's life, or your life, might be in danger. someone you don't know, who might not even have spoken to you, goes up to your bottom and puts their hand in your vagina. maybe several people. someone cuts your genitals. they insert something, or several things, into your vagina. sounds like rape to me. feels like rape to the women who told me stories like this one. 
when women feel supported and listened to, where they are treated respectfully, and involved in every decision, they experience the birth as positive, even if they receive every intervention under the sun. but when  woman are ignored, demeaned, denied, shouted out, and/or physically assaulted they are damaged by a traumatic life experience and are likely to suffer post traumatic stress disorder. 
we are seeing a rise in ptsd in women, and their birth partners, following birth. (continued in comments)

text:
‚Äúi barely even notice now when random men in public try to mess around because it's just such an everyday thing. 
however, i can vividly remember the first time it happened. i was 13.  i was waiting for my driver near my school when a guy in his early twenties on a red scooter pulled up and started cat calling. i didn‚Äôt look his way so he started to yell out "hey sexy, look over here baby". i looked over to give him a death stare only to see him waving about his penis at me. 
i froze in fear, literally could not stir a step and had no idea what to do- i thought of running to the traffic cop two streets down but the thought of approaching another man to report harassment scared me even further. 
i stayed rooted to the spot- until i saw a woman from the school off in the distance, whom i hurried over to and asked to help me. she chased him down with me but the pervert zipped away too soon for us to get his license number.

those 5 minutes made going back to school quite scary for weeks after.‚Äù
.
.
.
under section 294 of the ipc, acting obscenely in any public place, (including singing, reciting or uttering obscene songs or words) in or near any public space shall be punished with imprisonment for up to three months or fined, or both.

under section 509 of the ipc, uttering words, gesture or act intended to harm the modesty of a woman shall be punished with imprisonment for 2 years or with fine, or both.

#metoo #standagainstharassment #reclaimthestreets #fightsexualharassment #endviolenceagainstwomen #standup4humanrights #timesup #humanrights #unwomen #unwomenindia

text:
i was born and brought up in a small town in orissa called rourkela. and for the most part the onus of not being catcalled at or leered at was on me, the girl. so right from not wearing sleeveless tops or shorts so as to not attract unwanted attention to coming back home at 5.30 pm on the dot, i was the ideal girl. 
i have never spoken about this particular incident before mostly cause i've repressed it over the years as most such incidents that happen in your childhood are. because you are confused, tormented and even guilty for some strange reason. 
i was standing right outside the railway station talking to my dad. he had just turned way to put luggage into the car trunk when this guy, not more than 14 walked past me and stuck his hand between my legs. i froze completely because i was stunned. and the most unnerving thing was that my dad was right there. i could have easily said something to him then, but i was all of 10 and i had no idea what to make of what had happened to me and i don't think i even had the words to explain what i had felt at that point. 
that was my first introduction to the filthy world of abuse and it continues to happen. the only difference is that now instead of freezing, the response is a punch. it is scary how normalised abuse is. it is scary how consent is a luxury not a right.
.
.

name: Women Through The Lens
tweet_full:
i was born and brought up in a small town in orissa called rourkela. and for the most part the onus of not being catcalled at or leered at was on me, the girl. so right from not wearing sleeveless tops or shorts so as to not attract unwanted attention to coming back home at 5.30 pm on the dot, i was the ideal girl. 
i have never spoken about this particular incident before mostly cause i have repressed it over the years as most such incidents that happen in your childhood are. because you are confused, tormented and even guilty for some strange reason. 
i was standing right outside the railway station talking to my dad. he had just turned way to put luggage into the car trunk when this guy, not more than 14 walked past me and stuck his hand between my legs. i froze completely because i was stunned. and the most unnerving thing was that my dad was right there. i could have easily said something to him then, but i was all of 10 and i had no idea what to make of what had happened to me and i do not think i even had the words to explain what i had felt at that point. 
that was my first introduction to the filthy world of abuse and it continues to happen. the only difference is that now instead of freezing, the response is a punch. it is scary how normalised abuse is. it is scary how consent is a luxury not a right.
.
.
.
under section 354a of the ipc, making unwanted physical contact with a women against her will is punishable with rigorous imprisonment for a term which may extend to three years, or with fine, or both.

text:
i was given away by my family to become a devadasi at the age of 7. i was beaten up, roped and tortured by the man i was with, if i had known that being a devadasi would mean selling myself, i would have run away. i didn't know what it entailed, i wish i had known my what my fundamental rights were and if i had, i would not have tolerated this behaviour. i would have beaten the man back with a stick and left him. today, i understand what education does, it makes you strong, empowers you. i have endured a lifetime of torture and i will fight until my last breath to ensure that the children in my sangha have access to quality education that i didn't.
.
.
(aiyamma is the devadasi leader in raichur who has fought hard to make sure that families don't force young girls to take up this practice. she has gone door to door, spoken to hundreds of families to ensure that this practice comes to an end. whether it's negotiating with the government or ensuring that children attend school, she's in it, wholeheartedly) .
.
.
section 372 of the ipc prohibits selling minors for purpose of prostitution. immoral traffic (prevention) act, 1956, also makes prostitution in or the vicinity of public places an offence.
.

.
indonesia telah gagal melindungi korban kekerasan seksual secara hukum!
. 
sejak tahun 2012, ruu p-ks hanya tergeletak di atas meja ‚Äúwakil rakyat‚Äù kami di dpr, sehingga kasus-kasus seperti ibu nuril, agni, tuti trusilawati dan yang lainnya kerap bermunculan tanpa diakhiri dengan keadilan yang semestinya. menurut data @komnasperempuan, 35 orang perempuan menjadi korban kekerasan seksual setiap harinya. ini menunjukkan bahwa indonesia darurat dalam menangani kasus korban kekerasan seksual yang telah menjamur di negeri ini!
.
8 desember 2018 kemarin, bersama @sistersindanger, @simponi_id, dan banyak grup/aktivis lainnya dari berbagai kalangan (gender, ham, agamis), kami berjalan menuju depan istana untuk menuntut rancangan undang-undang penghapusan kekerasan seksual segera disahkan! #gerakbersama #metoo #hearmetoo #16haktp
.
p.s. saya tidak tergabung dengan fatayat nu, hanya memegang posternya...

text:
today is my 9 months sober of alcohol. everytime i mark this anniversary i realize how far i have come. i use to pop pills like candy, i use to be up for any drug except heroin or meth, i use to use sex to try and feel wanted, numb, or distracted. my life was an endless party, full of bad decisions, but many great friends, memories, and best of all lessons. if anything made all of this possible it was the prescription drugs i was forced on at 13. i just woke up one day to a life that no youth should have to lead and it broke me. i wanted to forget, which those times lead me to more things i'd like to forget.  eventually i realized that i couldnt forget and i couldnt stop the flashbacks. eventually i was mixing cocaine in capsules with adderall. eventually i was able to take 3 full bars of xanax, with vicodin, flexoril, and alcohol. the first 3 were my own prescriptions that my doctors refilled way too easily and willingly. eventually i was buying a 30 case and 2 fifths to share with friends, i drank half the case, and had a fifth to my self. eventually i lost all good in my life and went deep into a dark whole that lead me to my worst addiction ever, my exhusband. all of these things almost killed me. yet here i am, sober, looking at a sunrise. not after an all nighter and crawl drunkingly and high into my or someone elses bed, not hungover. 
i am alive, against the odds. i am here, and living proof that people can change!! now i'm going back to bed for an hour or so. i was also gifted with my period 4 days early today.  #sobriety #selflove #survivor #metoo #resilient #sober #lifetransformation #blogger #blog #motivation #selfcare #mentalhealth #mystory #dontgiveup #believeinyourself #bebold #bebrave #beyou #fuckbigpharma #endbigpharma
name: Jessica Martin(Meier)

text:
imelda cortez, a 20-year-old woman in el salvador who was jailed with attempted murder after she gave birth to her rapist's baby in a toilet has been freed. cortez was rushed to the hospital in april 2017 after she gave birth to a baby girl fathered by her stepfather, who has raped and sexually abused her since she was 12, in the toilet.

_  cortez said she did not know she was pregnant, but the doctor at the hospital suspected she had tried to abort the baby and called the authorities. cortez was then arrested and handed a 20 year jail sentence after prosecutors argued that failing to tell anyone about her pregnancy or seek medical attention for the baby amounted to attempted murder under the country‚Äôs laws, which completely bans abortions.

_

however, on monday, a court ruled that cortez had not tried to kill her child and that she was free to go home. the judge concluded that the court could not have expected her to act differently given the emotional and psychological damage inflicted by the sexual violence she had suffered since childhood. 
cortez was greeted by family members and supporters outside the courtroom. (üì∑: getty, reuters)
-

text:
earlier this year, a mere five months after the #metoo reckoning first began, a local tennessee television station dropped what should have been a bombshell investigation: three women were accusing state rep. david byrd of sexually assaulting them when they were minors in the 1980s, using his position as a girls‚Äô basketball coach to prey on players during team trips and after practices.

despite the seriousness of the allegations, the response within the state capital was, in a word, muted. by the end of the legislative session in april, just a few weeks after the investigation first hit, the calls for his resignation had dwindled, and byrd had announced he‚Äôd run for a third term in november. he overwhelmingly won reelection, with nearly 78 percent of the vote.

byrd has not exactly denied the allegations against him; rather, he emphasizes repeatedly that they are from more than 30 years ago. becca andrews has your must-read for the day. click the link in our bio to read it in its entirety‚Äîand to hear the stories of these women.
#women #news #politics #tennessee

text:
employees are the heart of any workplace. so, if organisations want to maintain a steady pulse they need to ensure that they create a safe and healthy work environment for each and every one of their employees. well-planned interventions in this regard can make a big difference in ensuring employee engagement, productivity and loyalty. .
.
however, many companies today compromise on the well-being of their employees due to the increasing pressure to achieve financial targets and stay competitive. they even measure the impact of employee training programmes in terms of direct financial gains. .
.
it‚Äôs important to remember that effective training programmes, especially on sensitive topics such as sexual harassment, can enable organisations to create a robust work culture that can offer long-term business sustainability. .
.
look beyond short-term gains. for more information, write to us at: shipra@be-artsy.com /akanksha@be-artsy.com. .

text:
denis mukwege and nadia murad have won the 2018 nobel peace prize for their efforts to end the use of sexual violence as a weapon in war. mukwege founded the panzi hospital in bukavu, in the east of the drc, where he has cared for tens of thousands of women who suffered sexual assault in the country's recent civil war. murad, a member of the yazidi minority in iraq, suffered rape and abuse by isis when her home village in northern iraq was attacked. she lost six brothers and her mother in the conflict. after her escape she has repeatedly spoken about her own sufferings and supported other victims.

text:
you cannot unpack hundreds of years of colonization, white supremacy, or patriarcy in 1 day. the work is constant. many women i know have begun their anti-racism journey and then when it feels hard they walk away. when the fear of discomfort shows up they step back.  discomfort, fear and fragility are reasons why you can't trust the process. 
now is not the time to step back. now is the time to show up to do the work. i'll post a video on this topic later today. .

and.. if you think you've mastered the work you're part of the problem

you may have gotten this life lesson early- i used to say when the secrets and tips to life were given out i must have been out back, probably smoking. üòâ

you have permission to leave what doesn‚Äôt serve you or meet your needs.  you have permission to search out help in your own healing, and giving women permission to heal around you. 
you have permission to leave situations you tolerated before and you are entitled to change.  and grow. 
goddess- this becoming is beautiful.  and if you stumble a little it‚Äôs all good.  find someone who is doing it and can love you through the process.  every day just a little bit better, a little more you.

text: this is how my hand (and probably many women's) looks like every time i get back home alone in the dark. why? because i don't feel safe. because every time i see a man in the same empty dark street i'm walking, my heart starts beating faster and harder. because if he's walking on the same side of the pavement as me, i unconsciously cross the street and walk faster, trying to not make any eye contact. because guys don't know what to feel this fear is. because some time ago i was walking back home after a night out. it was 8 in the morning and i was drunk. yes. it was 8am and i was drunk, because i wanted to, and because i could. it was june, almost summer, the sun was out and there was plenty of light. weather was already warm and nice and i was wearing a summer dress, a bit over the knees, not too "provocative" (for you victim-blaming fans out there). as i reached my street, i saw a guy getting off his car, he had just parked. "oh, probably just a neighbour" i thought and kept walking to my building. it was 8am and there was light. my keys fell to the ground and i picked them up. i got into my building, i usually close the door behind me to make sure nobody comes in after me (anti-rape protocol, i guess). that morning i didn't do it, alcohol makes you less vigilant and what the heck! it wasn't dark anymore, what could happen? as i was waiting for the lift i heard someone pushing the door. it was closed already. i turned around and saw the guy. he wasn't a neighbour from my building. he didn't open the door with any keys and he didn't ring any bell, he just moved forward and kept walking. i was left there, standing still, paralysed for a couple of seconds staring at the door, thinking what could have happened if it had been open. i guess i was lucky the door closed fast enough or the guy was too slow. this is my story, but there are many more. unfortunately, some girls weren't lucky enough to tell their stories like the girl who was murdered in my country a few days ago when she went just for a run. we want us alive. we want us free. we are not exaggerating. #metoo #cuentalo #niunamenos #women #feminist #feminism #feminicide #freedom #stopkillingus

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in 2014, steve bannon ‚Äì then executive chairman of the ‚Äúalt-right‚Äù news network breitbart ‚Äì was christopher wylie‚Äôs boss. and robert mercer, the secretive us hedge-fund billionaire and republican donor, was cambridge analytica‚Äôs investor. and the idea they bought into was to bring big data and social media to an established military methodology ‚Äì ‚Äúinformation operations‚Äù ‚Äì then turn it on the us electorate.

cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it‚Äôs insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it‚Äôs like nixon on steroids.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that‚Äôs what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him ‚Äúwe can take it.‚Äù no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it‚Äôs a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it‚Äôs easy to come along for the ride. there‚Äôs no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they‚Äôre both just characters on the television.

that‚Äôs what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it‚Äôs not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it‚Äôs that we‚Äôve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
sono #femminista, una parola bella che non tutti capiscono e che a qualcuno addirittura spaventa.
.
decido io della mia #vita, del mio #corpo e delle mie idee.
.
e non vorrei niente di meno per nessuna altra persona al mondo.
.
in questi giorni in casa va tutto alla malora, gli elettrodomestici si ribellano, la #doccia esplode e l'acqua calda sparisce.
.
per fare il #bagno devo attendere che ci sia abbastanza acqua nella #vasca, collezionata piano da decine di pentole messe sul fuoco.
.
ci vuole pazienza.
.
io non sempre la ho, sono abituata ad avere tutto subito, figlia della mia generazione.
.
quante cose diamo per scontate, quante occasioni, possibilit√† e #privilegi.
.
la #tecnologia e' una grande amica di noi esseri umani, senza di questa immagino che saremmo ancora ad ammuffire nelle cucine, invecchiare curvi nei campi e a fare la fila per tirar via l'acqua dal pozzo.
.
come #donne avremmo passato la vita a pulire lenzuola e lavare piatti, impiegando ore in cucina.
.
rimanendo in casa.
.
ci avrebbero sposate perch√© carine o rispettose e magari non avremmo potuto studiare ne' decidere se metter su' famiglia.
.
avremmo avuto ben poca voce in capitolo.
.
non e' un merito essere nati oggi, in questo secolo, ma sarebbe uno spreco non capire la nostra fortuna.
.
non invitare ad essere pari e solidali.
.
diversamente da chi ci ha preceduto: noi abbiamo #tempo, le possibilit√† e la consapevolezza di poter fare tanto ed in ogni campo.
.
equalmente e nel rispetto dei diritti di tutti.

text:
i‚Äôve done a bit of solo travel over the last couple years. i would highly recommend it, but instead of being totally glamorous and ‚Äúhigh vibe‚Äù about it, i will also speak to the pitfalls and the loneliness. fair warning: this post may trigger people. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
here is a picture of me when i ran off to california a couple years ago for an impromptu trip across the country. i went out there to meet my ex, and to spend some time on my own in la. during the trip, he told me that ‚Äúother girls he‚Äôs been with just knew how to please him sexually, but somehow i just couldn‚Äôt figure it out. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
i left him feeling weak and vulnerable- couldn‚Äôt he see that i traveled across the country to hang out with him? why wasn‚Äôt that enough? i was hurt and alone, my mind racing and my body disconnected.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
after i left the southern most point of california and headed to venice beach, i was sitting on the sand somewhat perplexed. i read a good book and started to feel like a human again. before i knew it, some seemingly nice hippie approached me and asked if i wanted a ‚Äúreiki‚Äù session; he was recently certified and wanted to practice his newfound skills. he was fairly persistent, in hindsight, a red flag i missed. i finally said, okay sure- already feeling weak and fighting for my center from the previous day‚Äôs gaslighting. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
as he started to do the ‚Äúreiki‚Äù i became uncomfortable and opened my eyes, revealing his hands grabbing my boobs with a sick look in his eye. i immediately got up and ran away. he did not bother chasing me. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
i didn‚Äôt really talk to anyone about it. i felt like the idiot for letting my guard down so some pervert hippie could grope me. i was alone, a tourist in a beach town- and i was in a vulnerable state of mind.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
so whether you‚Äôre solo traveling, or existing in your home town- take good care of yourself. pay attention to the people around you & keep your focus clear. abuse drains you of your vital energy, it robs you of strength and discernment. ‚Ä¢

text: child advocacy centers are set up for forensic interviews to be conducted for the multi disciplinary team. the child advocacy center is a child friendly environment and the interviewer is trained to take a child's statement about their abuse. they ask all of the appropriate questions and share their findings with law enforcement, social workers, therapists, and all other interested parties who are legally allowed to access this information. the forensic interview can be videotaped so interested parties can review it as needed. interested parties may also provide questions for the interviewer to include in their session to ensure all necessary information is included for a thorough investigation. the purpose of the forensic interview is to eliminate the need for multiple interviews to be conducted by every agency who has a role in the case. this process is effective, but it doesn't always eliminate multiple interviews, as some agencies may still request their own independent interview. if this happens, please do not allow that to discourage you or your child from participating in the case. #comfortinthestorm #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #family

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

.
.
.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

earlier this year, a mere five months after the #metoo reckoning first began, a local tennessee television station dropped what should have been a bombshell investigation: three women were accusing state rep. david byrd of sexually assaulting them when they were minors in the 1980s, using his position as a girls‚Äô basketball coach to prey on players during team trips and after practices.

despite the seriousness of the allegations, the response within the state capital was, in a word, muted. by the end of the legislative session in april, just a few weeks after the investigation first hit, the calls for his resignation had dwindled, and byrd had announced he‚Äôd run for a third term in november. he overwhelmingly won reelection, with nearly 78 percent of the vote.

byrd has not exactly denied the allegations against him; rather, he emphasizes repeatedly that they are from more than 30 years ago. becca andrews has your must-read for the day. click the link in our bio to read it in its entirety‚Äîand to hear the stories of these women.

text:
this gender inclusive version of my poem "she'll find the sky" is going to be included at the end of the short film "joan's song" directed by @natashastraley. the theme of the film is domestic abuse. i'm excited that the film will be entering into the 2019 film festival circuit. i will be adding this version of the poem to my etsy poetry store soon. the link to my poetry store is in my bio. üíï .
.
i hope this poem reaches someone who needs it today. you are not alone and there is hope. you are stronger than you think. you are worthy of love that doesn't hurt, you deserve to be treated with dignity and respect. you were not put on this earth to be somebody's punching bag, whether it's physically or emotionally. you must protect yourself from anyone who harms your spirit. .
.

text:
had a great afternoon speaking to the high school girls of @garrison_forest about overcoming adversity & developing resilience!
‚Ä¢
in sharing my story of growing up in a home of addiction and mental illness which resulted in the loss of my mother, it is my goal to empower girls to say #metoo . one of the beautiful things about the #metoo movement to me is that its core message allows humans to realize they are not alone in their pain and suffering. it invites them to be a part of a community of people who have experienced the darkness that comes with living, so that they can collectively find the light.
‚Ä¢
this is why i share my story. because i know i‚Äôm not alone, and i want other young women to know they‚Äôre not alone either. we are all in this together. as the brilliant rabbi and author, ram das, writes, ‚Äúin the end we are just walking each other home.‚Äù
‚Ä¢
i‚Äôll walk you home, my loves. i‚Äôll hold your hand while we walk, too. üíï
‚Ä¢

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
got in a bit of a fight with a man on the internet this past week who was espousing that it was time to move on from the #metoo moment and enter into a more collaborative conversation with men. my take is this: there are so many stories that still haven't been shared. so many women that will never feel safe or have the privileges required to speak out. the time for listening is not over. men have carried power and control over the consent conversation for all of time. they need to sit tight and keep listening for longer than just a year and some change....these are just some of my thoughts. i'd be very curious to hear yours.

text:
in a world where we want women to be quiet, speak loud. 
in a world where we want women to be small, dare to take some space. 
in a world where we want women to obey, dare to contest. 
i know it is no easy - because we have always reduced women to their physical appearance. 
that subconsciously, we internalized it - we have to be pretty / appealing / skinny / to please men. that we almost prioritize it on who we really want to be ‚ù£Ô∏è but the person you really need to please, is yourself. 
and believe me, if we dig a little bit, there‚Äôs much more to it than just your reflection in the mirror. 
make sure that the woman you are pleases you. 
make sure the values she embodies pleases you. 
make sure the life she has chosen pleases you. 
you live for you, before living for anyone else üí´ 
_____________________________________________
dans un monde o√π on veut que les femmes soient silencieuses, osez prendre la parole. 
dans un monde o√π on veut que les femmes se fassent petites, osez prendre de la place. 
dans un monde o√π l‚Äôon veut que les femmes ob√©issent, osez contester. 
je sais que ce n‚Äôest pas facile - car on a toujours r√©duit les femmes √† leur apparence physique. qu‚Äôinconsciemment, on l‚Äôint√®gre nous-m√™mes - il faut qu‚Äôon soit belle / attirante / mince / qu‚Äôon plaise aux hommes. qu‚Äôon place limite cela en priorit√© de qui l‚Äôon veut √™tre
‚ù£Ô∏è mais la personne √† qui vous devez plaire, c‚Äôest vous. 
et croyez-moi, si on creuse bien, il s‚Äôagit plus que d‚Äôun simple reflet dans le miroir. 
faites que la femme que vous √™tes vous plaise. 
que les valeurs qu‚Äôelle repr√©sente vous plaise. 
que la vie qu‚Äôelle a choisit vous plaise. 
vous existez pour vous, avant d‚Äôexister pour qui que ce soit d‚Äôautre üí´ .
.
.

text:
‚Äúmore than you‚Äôll ever know‚Äù
acrylic . 20x20‚Äù march 2017 . (i love you) more than you‚Äôll ever know. .

how often do we forget we are loved?  we forget love and leave it lying in the corner of a hallway.  walking by it all day not acknowledging it‚Äôs presence.  we keep our thoughts fixed on ‚Äúthem.‚Äù that other person who seems to have more than i in all the ways i want. .

but do you really know their story?  maybe they too have forgotten how loved they are.  they just ‚Äúlook‚Äù better at keeping themselves together. .

when we are loved and known it‚Äôs amazing how it changes the entirety of a person.  how they think about themselves, think about others, how they act to themselves and to others. .

it‚Äôs so easy to forget this.  so easy to not be thankful for what you have (and don‚Äôt have). i think a heart of thankfulness might be the best gift one could ever give (and receive). .

all the marketing campaigns of the holidays drive me crazy and sometimes i get caught up in their current of nonsense.  i have to remind myself to slow down, remind myself what i already have.  when i do this, you‚Äôll prob see a big fat smile on my face cuz there is a lot of goodness and people and experiences that i‚Äôm so incredibly grateful for.  i just have to remember... .

but do you really know their story?  maybe they too have forgotten how loved they are.  they just ‚Äúlook‚Äù better at keeping themselves together. .

when we are loved and known it‚Äôs amazing how it changes the entirety of a person.  how they think about themselves, think about others, how they act to themselves and to others. .

it‚Äôs so easy to forget this.  so easy to not be thankful for what you have (and don‚Äôt have). i think a heart of thankfulness might be the best gift one could ever give (and receive). .

„Éª„Éª„Éª
we find some survivors stories easier to believe than others, and that has alot to do with our ideas about what constitutes sexual assault.
-
it's easier for us as a society to accept the "scary stranger in a dark ally at night" - but most assault actually rarely happens this way.
-
it also has to do with ideas about who is deemed "credible" - prejudice and stereotypes held around race, class, age, gender identity, sexuality play a part too.
-
there is no such thing as a ‚Äúcredible‚Äù survivor. all survivors should be believed in their truth, regardless of their lifestyle and who they are!
-
let's be critical as a society about who's stories are taken as credible and why. let's listen to survivors in their bravery and truth.

text:
hurricanes
tornadoes
tsunamis
volcanic eruptions
woman

strong
fierce
and beautiful too

nothing is stronger
than her trying to
build herself again
strong as the winds
fierce as the lava
beautiful as the high waves

the word "woman" in itself is so
unfathomably strong
that at times she forgets her worth
she's shines brighter than diamonds

what could be more glorious than this?
.
to be as strong as force of nature
to be wild
to be of your own
to own yourself without
any guilt or regret

embrace the glorious
mess that you are
love your freckles
love your thighs
love yourself
start with yourself¬†
become what you dreamt of
empower women

be a force that people love to look at your work

build castles when they throw bricks at you

go fierce for a while and then forever
leave a mark in their heads

for hurricanes and earthquakes 
weren't just named after
woman like that.
.
.
palak agrawal.
(@uncaged_musings)
.
.

just when i thought i worked through it all, being in service the last few weeks again made me come to the realization that i didn‚Äôt fully. i came to the realization that i had shared my experiences in a safe environment, at a few relevant settings and with some trusted few. i had not fully brought the situation into light to break the cycle. i still lived in fear with lots to lose, without wanting to see what‚Äôs on the other side. ‚õÖÔ∏è.
today i stand certain that no matter how risky things get, i‚Äôm choosing me, choosing life, and choosing light. if we are not a part of the solution, then we are a part of the problem. more to come... #togetherwerise. üåé

anyway....with 2018 being almost over i wanted to do a little bit of a transformation post.... this has probably been one of the toughest, challenging, most eye opening years i have ever had. i was pushed, pulled, stretched, knocked down, torn and beaten down. i hit so low that i had to go up to hit rock bottom.... that being said, however hard this year was, i would never change it for the world. this year has taught me so much. i truly found my self worth. i became one with god and continue to grow in my relationship with him. i been broken but then mended and healed and became stronger. i grew so much mentally, physically and emotionally. i fell in love with myself and all that i am. i learned that sometimes you have to break to become whole. i learned that tough times don‚Äôt last. i learned that no matter how hard times get there is always something to look forward to. i learned so much about myself and my mental health and my inner strength. i explored so many new places. met so many new people and lost some old people. i gained weight and lost weight. i got good grades and failed classes. i had a lot of money and i had no money. i felt like i was on top of the world and felt like i didn‚Äôt wanna live anymore. i went through hoops and obstacles.  i had so much hope and lost all hope. i made many mistakes and learned from each and every on. no matter how hard this year was i wouldn‚Äôt change a thing. this year pushed me harder than i ever experienced but i grew and learned so much.  no matter what 2019 brings i will face it head on and grow and learn. i got this far and already learned so much. i can‚Äôt wait to see where next year takes me. so here‚Äôs to new beginnings, new people, new expired, new lessons and new challenges

text:
assault is everywhere.

assault can happen to anyone, anywhere, by anyone- family, foe, or best friend.

now, i‚Äôm not saying this to scare you but to warn you. life is beautiful, but it can be scary too. i‚Äôve been assaulted multiple times by someone i loved and thought loved me, i was only twelve and thirteen. assault, harassment, it's no joke- no lighthearted trauma. it stays with you forever, being forced- manipulated, assaulted, it doesn‚Äôt go away. though the sting of your skin may lesson with time.

a couple weeks ago, a friend of mine was assaulted by a boy who she thought was a close friend. she‚Äôd been assaulted far too many times before, but with the wrong people surrounding her it continued to happen with different people. i‚Äôve yelled at the boy, he finds himself innocent. her father is mad, saying it isn‚Äôt what it is- rape. saying she‚Äôs making a big fuss and trying to ruin someone's life, she‚Äôs not. she‚Äôs having to ditch people who don‚Äôt support her or are toxic, she has to deal with this- clown of a parent. the reason i post this is because she needs support, she‚Äôs admitted it to me and i want to do all i can- so please. share you‚Äôre warmest regards, not because she‚Äôs weak- not because she‚Äôs a victim- but because even the strongest people can‚Äôt withstand the hardest times alone. we need each others support and emotion and love, we need to stick together- to speak out. to be loud.

dominic helped me speak aloud with polygraph eyes, now i‚Äôm damn down to make sure that others feel that same freedom to be loud. its not something to be proud of, its a scar- its a war scar. you survived, how badass is that
please please comment support

i love you sweetheart, friend, cuteness. it‚Äôll get better.

even if you will, i will never shut up. üñ§ .

text:
mm holiday challenge day 1 & 2! 
giving and receiving and random acts of kindness challenge. 
i am a recovering over giver and people pleaser. i used to give it all. always to everyone because i thought that is what love looked like. receiving wasn‚Äôt even really in my awareness. it is now after my 3rd time through this challenge!!! random acts of kindness bring me joy and is a form of receiving joy for me and something i am always doing. complimenting those who look like they need an energetic hug, helping older people who are struggling in the store, patting random dogs and sending them reiki, donating things and time, and smiling and making eye contact with strangers. this all happened in the last two days as i prepared, packed and mailed care packages to my loved ones and made the experience really joyfilled. i am practicing receiving more. more help, more support, and letting more love in. my puppy was the best teacher for me with this practice this year, grieving the loss of my dad and also my very best friend, i had some serious fear of love showing up, my dog is slowly softening and melting my fears. he is reminding me it is safe to deeply love and be deeply loved back.  even for brief moments and knowing heartbreak and saying goodbye is part of the deal of loving deeply. a life filled with deep love also includes deep pain. it is still worth it. and i need every day of this challenge again for this holiday season where it feels like there are too many empty.

you can still join this 24 day self care challenge in my bio above. 
#mmholidaychallenge2018 , #mmholidaychallenge , #lifecoachforwomen, #metoo, #timesup ,#holistichealer, #reiki #restorativeyoga, #embodiment

text: summary of 2018 (right to left from bottom right): discovering what amazing fabrics i ordered while shopping + drinking cocktails; discovering that ric rack makes an awesome piping; discovering the solidarity that came from sharing our #metoo stories with one another; discovering the magic of japan and leaving a little #travelingmoes love behind; standing in drop-jawed awe when #emiliaholden did the body slam we all wish we would have done once in our lives; dressing up to head to the kids‚Äô school and make a good impression, but maybe also not taking off the sports bra because, for reals, y‚Äôall; sewing more in 2018 for myself than in the past two or three years combined and feeling it; soaking in the joy and privilege of living in a home @dadcation and i crafted together with love, dreams, hope and a little bit of chewing gum; and finally, allowing myself to take deep pride in the @murdermysteryquilt, which along with the @leagueofdressmakers has grown beyond my wildest dreams from when i first launched it, and become the first professional venture in which i have ever engaged where i can‚Äôt wait to talk about my work. it has been a hell of a year‚Äîso much of it beyond good, some a little hellish, and i am a vastly better human at this end of it. a new year always seems like an arbitrary dividing line, i acknowledge, but i am excited for what the next 12 months brings, and for who i will be as i meet it. here‚Äôs to growth, courage, comfort, love, safety, and warmth for all of us. ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è #gratefulheart #top9of2018
